g Zinc for compilation. However, it seems Java files under Scala source directories may not be recognized. There’s also the consideration of how task order works between Java and Scala. It looks like I need to verify the configuration and explore options to manage compilation effectively. I hope to streamline this and avoid unnecessary complications!\n[thinking] \n[thinking] **Exploring mixed compilation configuration**\n[thinking] \n[thinking] I'm wondering if the Scala source set actually includes both `**/*.scala` and `**/*.java` files. It seems like standard mixed compilation in Gradle may expect Java sources to be placed within Scala source directories. I should double-check if this setup already exists in my project. I might need to search for more information or examples on this to ensure everything is set up correctly for successful mixed compilation. It’s all about finding that balance!\n[thinking] \n[assistant-event] thinking_end\n[tool-call] start id=unknown\n[tool-call] delta {\"command\":\"find tests/src -path '*/src/test/scala/*.java' -o -path '*/src/test/scala/**/*.java' | head -20\",\"timeout\":10}\n[tool-call] end id=call_O3ZO6kUMBlScHlOGVphaEMH5|fc_0d0da3d6c2f079ff016a29671b63ec8197bc28916ca4f019f3 name=bash args={\"command\": \"find tests/src -path '*/src/test/scala/*.java' -o -path '*/src/test/scala/**/*.java' | head -20\", \"timeout\": 10}\n[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering compilation order**\\n\\nI'm pondering whether to move the Java helper to src/test/scala, ensuring it gets included during the compile process. The SourceSet.scala seems to account for src/test/scala only, while Java source in src/test/java might be compiled before ScalaCompile. That could mean Scala can't reference it if compileJava occurs first. I wonder if test Java compile needs to happen after the main compilation. Also, does compileTestScala depend on compileTestJava or vice versa? Good questions to sort out!\\n\\n**Clarifying Scala and Java compilation**\\n\\nI'm looking into the `compileJava` task, specifically how source sets work with Java and Scala files. The docs suggest that the Scala plugin can mix both types of sources, using Zinc for compilation. However, it seems Java files under Scala source directories may not be recognized. There’s also the consideration of how task order works between Java and Scala. It looks like I need to verify the configuration and explore options to manage compilation effectively. I hope to streamline this and avoid unnecessary complications!\\n\\n**Exploring mixed compilation configuration**\\n\\nI'm wondering if the Scala source set actually includes both `**/*.scala` and `**/*.java` files. It seems like standard mixed compilation in Gradle may expect Java sources to be placed within Scala source directories. I should double-check if this setup already exists in my project. I might need to search for more information or examples on this to ensure everything is set up correctly for successful mixed compilation. It’s all about finding that balance!\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0d0da3d6c2f079ff016a296702e3348197a1588494bd4c3aad\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"content\\\":[],\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqKWcbNRhUo5qMuDTJAZYzSlA5cgnYk-Ijw0A6XpcWwVdwMq2S3A2qb94ClXrCQugZvrZP0AEZqiDQcI2mXx6nw_vs1cvvRiD-PCyro2pmkd4L0wLLu37mEC-uEaLKQp_uJGas-Feh7StZ7RO-tLjHpgJ_0pyhEkxGNoYjNd-wFgjZW3FRfSeZviuwzHOHdTFGUzfmiMzDKjr2-dAykD7bfNWVTxWKwiPNvH0aaodbywGuZpMHOII2TqNWo_vxeeBUDE2gtBqgHCE8h1QChXHecMwm8lJznsqbKboW4JeLNmhVcZN0qhNI8SL8uTYNUtSM6Q5v1Zg-GOBBQwUozMT-tz-dbpwmpWtpgwmXt22rDyBq6a35g7bXUZGPWeNeINxoi_BP2-nKXhUPRDgAtlN4Hgy6vKtyCOJ5vt-h343BCWanzOVhjKIpayIP3_1f9qYpyMkeqQHeeTSLQGqSZwdJ3VO9l5EHFrcHE5YF0xDCRvX668scS1pDqMNmaE-PA2E8O4f9SE0IPYECfggohoLKDB0X7XtlMlK9hzdqy8BIJKGgQEAgqZ_Tjp52_CKTTIElbcng4xNuhVTdaunaOynA02TUZxcL1G2PnlJUZ7x4pXID8UKYQU0g0Jkp6QdpYLHl-GEL05kumEZWYk7bP_iIQKMy6